# GitHub Deep Search user key configuration
#
# How to use:
# 1. Copy this file to: config/user_keys.env
# 2. Fill in the values below.
# 3. Restart the Web server or rerun the CLI command.
#
# Do not commit config/user_keys.env to Git. It is ignored by .gitignore.

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Required: GitHub token
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Why this is needed:
# - Searches GitHub repositories.
# - Fetches public repository metadata and README files.
# - Avoids GitHub's very low unauthenticated API quota.
#
# Recommended token type:
# - Fine-grained Personal Access Token.
# - Public repository read-only usage is enough for this tool.
# - Do not grant write permissions.
# - Do not grant private repository access unless you intentionally want that.
#
# How to create it:
# 1. Open GitHub Settings:
#    https://github.com/settings/tokens?type=beta
# 2. Click "Generate new token".
# 3. Set a clear name, for example: github-deep-search-local
# 4. Choose an expiration date.
# 5. Repository access:
#    - Public repositories only, or
#    - Only selected repositories if you later adapt the tool for private repos.
# 6. Permissions:
#    - Metadata: Read-only
#    - Contents: Read-only is useful for README/content access when needed.
# 7. Generate and copy the token.
#
# Official docs:
# https://docs.github.com/en/authentication/keeping-your-account-and-data-secure/managing-your-personal-access-tokens
GITHUB_TOKEN=

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Required for high-quality analysis: OpenAI-compatible LLM key
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Why this is needed:
# - Converts natural-language requirements into better search queries.
# - Compares README content against the user's feature requirements.
# - Generates cleaner difference analysis and opportunity judgment.
#
# OpenAI:
# 1. Open the OpenAI Platform API keys page:
#    https://platform.openai.com/api-keys
# 2. Create a new API key.
# 3. Copy it into LLM_API_KEY below.
#
# Other OpenAI-compatible providers:
# - DeepSeek, OpenRouter, local gateways, or other compatible services can work.
# - Set LLM_BASE_URL to that provider's /v1 endpoint.
# - Set LLM_MODEL to the model name from that provider.
#
# DeepSeek example, according to current official docs:
# - LLM_BASE_URL=https://api.deepseek.com
# - LLM_MODEL=deepseek-v4-flash
# - LLM_THINKING=disabled
# Use deepseek-v4-pro when quality matters more than speed/cost.
#
# Official OpenAI quickstart:
# https://developers.openai.com/api/docs/quickstart
LLM_API_KEY=
LLM_BASE_URL=https://api.openai.com/v1
LLM_MODEL=gpt-5-mini

# Optional provider-specific parameters.
# DeepSeek supports thinking mode:
# - disabled: faster and cheaper, recommended for this lightweight search tool.
# - enabled: stronger reasoning, slower and more expensive.
LLM_THINKING=
LLM_REASONING_EFFORT=

# Optional cost estimation knobs.
# Fill these with your provider's current price if you want dollar estimates.
# Unit: USD per 1M input/output tokens. Leave as 0 to report token usage only.
LLM_INPUT_USD_PER_1M=0
LLM_OUTPUT_USD_PER_1M=0

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Optional but recommended: Tavily API key
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Why this is useful:
# - Cross-checks GitHub results with Web search.
# - Finds GitHub projects mentioned in articles, awesome lists, docs, and blogs.
# - Helps reduce "GitHub search keyword mismatch" misses.
#
# How to create it:
# 1. Open Tavily Platform:
#    https://app.tavily.com/
# 2. Sign in or create an account.
# 3. Copy an API key from your dashboard.
#
# Official docs:
# https://docs.tavily.com/documentation/quickstart
TAVILY_API_KEY=
TAVILY_USD_PER_CREDIT=0.008

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Runtime limits for the default light report
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# These are safety limits to prevent accidental API overuse.
# You usually do not need to change them.
MAX_GITHUB_REQUESTS=40
MAX_TAVILY_CREDITS=4
MAX_CANDIDATES=30
MAX_DEEP_ANALYZE_REPOS=3
TASK_DEADLINE_SECONDS=70
